            <div type="translation">
                <p>Πέτρῳ ὑπάτῳ καὶ ἐπὶ τῶν βαρβάρων / Πέτρῳ ὑπάτῳ καὶ ἐπὶ τῶν βαρβάρων.</p>
                <p xml:lang="en">Petros hypatos and epi ton barbaron. Petros hypatos and epi ton barbaron.</p>
                <p xml:lang="de">Petros hypatos und epi ton barbaron. Petros hypatos und epi ton barbaron.</p>
              </div>
            <div type="commentary" subtype="text">
                <p xml:lang="en">The restitution of the circular inscription is based on the parallel. There is a whole series of other seals (with different iconography) naming a Petros <hi rend="italic">hypatos</hi> and <hi rend="italic">epi ton barbaron</hi>.[1]</p>                 
              </div>
            <div type="commentary" subtype="footnotes"><!-- C. Sode, Reaching Beyond the Borders of the Byzantine Empire: The Seals of the epi ton barbaron, in XXX, Byzantium in China: Studies in Honour of Professor Xu Jialing on the Occasion of her Seventieth Birthday, Changchun 2019, p. 173-193. in bibliography ergänzen-->
                <p xml:id="footnote-1">[1]. <bibl><ptr target="DOsealsOnline"/>, <citedRange unit="entry"><ref target="https://www.doaks.org/resources/seals/byzantine-seals/BZS.1951.31.5.2593/">BZS.1951.31.5.2593</ref></citedRange></bibl>, also published in <bibl><ptr target="Zacos1"/>, no. <citedRange unit="entry">3003a-c</citedRange></bibl>. On the office see also <bibl><ptr target="Sode2019"/></bibl>.</p>
              </div>
